# Journal doc writing (AI instructions)

When creating or editing files under `apps/docs/docs/journal/`, follow this guide.

## Purpose

Standalone learning pages: what was built, how it works, in the author's words. Each page reads alone — **no links** to other site sections or journal pages. Mention follow-up topics by title only.

## Language & tone

- **Banglish**: Bangla explanations; English for technical terms (CORS, proxy, `fetch`, token, stream, env, API, component names).
- **Tutorial / module voice**: direct, factual, structured — like a course section.
- **Avoid**: diary or confession tone, dramatic arcs (“মনে হয়েছিল… আসলে…”), “ধাক্কা” storytelling, hype, filler (“In this article we will explore”, “It is important to note”, long conclusions that repeat the intro).
- **Avoid**: English-only unless the user asks.

## Structure

1. **Title** — `# <topic>` (clear, includes English term when useful).
2. **Intro** — 2–4 sentences: what this page covers + prerequisites (tools, running app) only.
3. **Numbered sections** — `## ১.` / `## ২.` or `## 1.` / `## 2.` (pick one style per doc).
4. **Use when they teach** (not mandatory every page):
   - Table (states, config keys, component roles)
   - One short analogy (max one paragraph)
   - Minimal code/config from the repo
   - Example output (UI string, request path, terminal snippet)
5. **End** — one `> [!TIP]` or `> [!NOTE]` with a practical rule; optional **Boundary** line: what this page does *not* cover.

Keep paragraphs short (2–4 lines). Optional section emojis (`## 💻`) only if the series already uses them.

## Scope & depth

- **One topic per page.** Do not bundle unrelated subjects.
- **Repo-grounded**: real paths, env vars, functions from `apps/chat-web` (or the app named in the task). Do not invent features; note unused env vars briefly if relevant.
- **Shallow by default** — only go deep when the user asks. Skip production hardening, full API reference, and unrelated providers unless the page title requires them.

## Technical habits

- Separate **CLI/Node** (direct URL, no CORS) vs **browser** (same-origin, dev proxy) when relevant.
- Name concrete artifacts: e.g. `VITE_OLLAMA_URL`, `vite.config.js`, `OllamaStatus`, `checkOllamaHealth`.
- Docusaurus front matter when needed: `sidebar_position`, `title`.

## Voice checklist (before finishing)

- [ ] Reads as a textbook section, not a personal blog rant
- [ ] No first-person drama unless the user explicitly requests narrative style
- [ ] At least one concrete example (config, path, or UI text)
- [ ] Boundary stated if the topic could bleed into neighbors (streaming, context, RAG, etc.)

## Anti-patterns

- Wall of bullets with no prose
- Repeating the same point in intro, body, and tip
- Long essay for a narrow topic (e.g. proxy + status = one page, not five)
- Cross-links or “see also” URLs to other docs

## When the user gives a topic

Confirm or produce: title, numbered outline, draft depth (outline vs full), **out of scope** list, and source files in the repo to cite.
